These sentences seem to be good examples demonstrating that an intransitive V with a resultative complement can make an acceptable ba sentence, with the ba NP interpreted as the subject of the resultative complement. Closer examination of a wider range of data, however, reveals that the generalization may not be quite true. There are many instances where a result expression does not make a ba sentence with an intransitive verb acceptable. For instance, the following sentences contain a resultative complement after an intransitive verb;
